metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse‚Ä¶ which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

metadata.name: Disegnatori #159
metadata.description:
Each disegnatore learns a different portion of a city map, looking at it stroke by stroke and creating a probabilistic Markov model of the sequences of relative angles and distances, tracing the outline of each building in that portion of the map. This way, each disegnatore has a different internal understanding of the city.

It then starts from the middle of the canvas and wanders out, stroke by stroke, probability by probability, trying not to intersect any previously drawn outlines and avoiding the edges of the canvas until a predetermined number of edges have been drawn.

The Markov chain drawing model is created during execution from a text file representation of a city map.

Open live to see your disegnatore drawing or to resize.

metadata.name: Protein Pelt #127
metadata.description:
An incorrectly placed decimal point led to this pattern. A good friend told me it reminded them of protein structures, I found them to look like animal pelts strewn about.

Each "protein" is made up of 100 pelts, random walking around the canvas from the center. Each "pelt" is made of 5 colors sampled from an array of 84 colors.

Press 's' when in live view to save the image.

metadata.name: Euphonic #58
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moir√© effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: ARAUCO #49
metadata.description:
The Araucaria Araucana, also known as pew√©n, is a sacred tree for the Mapuche and an emblem of Chile. With an origin dating back 260 million years to the Triassic period, it is part of the oldest forests on the planet. These ancient trees are endangered due to logging, forest fires, and grazing.

ARAUCO is a tribute to araucarias and Mapuche iconography. Incorporating elements such as the Kultrung, the W√ºnelfe star, and the staggered cross Ng√ºmin, the work displays a typical landscape of southern Chile with the Andes Mountains in the background and the native forest. 

‚Äì

Press 's' to export a 4960x7016 PNG file suitable for A2 printing at 300 dpi.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: FraKtuR #4
metadata.description:
"I am fascinated by the fragmentation process. Chinese porcelain makers used it as a decorative technique for the so-called "crackle" type of porcelain. The most famous crackle porcelains come from China from the 12th century to the Song period, and it is a pleasure to recreate such an ancient and rich technique into an algorithm.

- Olivier Bodini"

FraKtuR simulates the porcelain-making process: 
1) recursively fragment a polygon
2) apply a Gaussian blur to make the fragmentation irregular 
3) apply colors to each fragment 
4) texturize the work with marked noise, per fragment.

----------------

FraKtuR was part of the Blind Gallery Seed Edition (6th-15th, Feb 2023)
Learn more at www.BlindGallery.xyz

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #109
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #123
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: monogrid 1.1 CE #99
metadata.description:
Each monogrid artwork gets initialized with a start up algorithm that builds up a set of rectangles and fills them with pixels. There are two different styles, 'Pixel' and 'Line', to create the initial image.

There is a set of 16 animations at work. 4 noise based animations, 4 shifting animations, 4 modulo based animation and 4 reset animations, all run in parallel. Each animation selects a rectangle from the initial setup and edits the pixels in this area. The selection process runs independently and animations can overlap which results in a new style of animation.

monogrid 1.1 is based on the original series at https://monogrid.xyz, but there are no black/white versions included. The color palette is a mixture of one of 12 colors plus black or white.
The fragment shader has been updated in the way the 16 different animations get summed up. This version would appear more chaotic and organic.

monogrid 1.1 - Collectors Edition
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #169
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #202
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Love Poem #15
metadata.description:
Love is a very complex feeling,

The definition of love would be different if we ask 300 people in the same room. Although uniquely different to each other, most people would agree on how complex love could be, especially if it‚Äôs directed towards something that‚Äôs not quite humane; neither alive, nor is it dead.

‚ÄúLove Poem‚Äù is one of the conveyor and translator of that feeling.

The unique and abstracted iterations of different love poems made through the distinctive pixelart style of MEK.txt and the coding diligence and brilliance of IceRain, are the innocent attempt the two brewed to help people convey and interpret how their form of love poems could be.

‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢

All of the visuals in this project are 100% code.
